INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (3,1,'2009-11-17 14:02:22','2009-11-17 14:02:22','<p>I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s what I did:</p>\r\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\r\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\r\n','Wordpress in a lunch break','','publish','open','open','','wordpress-in-a-lunch-break','','','2010-02-27 21:50:32','2010-02-27 21:50:32','',0,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/?p=3',0,'post','',0);
