INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (31,1,'2010-03-27 13:56:56','2010-03-27 13:56:56','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\r\n\r\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\r\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis will create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\r\n\r\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','publish','open','open','','branching-with-tortoise-svn','','','2010-05-05 11:42:32','2010-05-05 10:42:32','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=31',0,'post','',0);
